Every control and every application has to belong to a Business Unit — that's how the platform knows who to ask for evidence, who's accountable, and where audit trails should land. In the past, this was institutional knowledge — someone in the team just knew who owned what, or it lived in a spreadsheet that often went stale.
The platform replaces that with two simple setups, done once.
The first is for business processes. There are only a handful, and they rarely change. The Risk Manager picks each process from a list and points it to its Business Unit. For example, the Risk Management process belongs to the Engineering Business Unit. IT Change Management belongs to Platform Engineering. One process, one Business Unit. Easy to maintain. Easy to audit.
The second is for applications. LeanIX already knows where each application sits in the organization — it stores a path like Bank slash Wealth slash PlatformOps. The Risk Manager defines short patterns that the platform watches for. When the platform sees that path, the pattern Wealth slash PlatformOps tells it: this application belongs to the Wealth Business Unit. Set the patterns once; the platform applies them to every application, every cycle.
And every row has a status. Mapped means the platform resolved it cleanly. Unresolved means the platform couldn't find a match — the Risk Manager either adds a pattern, an explicit mapping, or marks the row Ignored if it intentionally has no owner. Some processes are Horizontal — they cross multiple Business Units, like security policy or governance frameworks. The platform recognizes that pattern too. Blank Business Units aren't errors; they're work items, surfaced by the platform so nothing falls through the cracks
